{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7fe7a092-24c5-4342-bd59-97dc00df230c","content":"## The Issue\n\n**.NET MAUI Android builds ignore `JAVA_HOME`**. Since .NET 8, the `android` workload bundles its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and uses it via the MSBuild property `$(JavaSdkDirectory)`, which takes precedence. Your Temurin JDK is never used by the build.\n\n## Fixes (pick one)\n\n**Option 1 — Reinstall/repair the bundled JDK (recommended):**\n```bash\ndotnet workload repair\n# or\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Tell MSBuild to use your Temurin JDK:**\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj` inside a `<PropertyGroup>`:\n```xml\n<JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n```\n\n**Option 3 — Set it globally via `Directory.Build.props`** in your solution root (same property as above), so it applies to all projects.\n\nAfter applying a fix, do a clean rebuild:\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet build -t:Run -f net8.0-android\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6bc67dfa-c46d-485c-959d-6b6b324b78da","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI Android build failure related to Java. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed. Let me think about what the common issue is here.\n\nThis is a well-known issue: .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK build tools require JDK 17, but there's a specific issue with .NET MAUI and JDK versions.\n\nActually, the most common issue is that .NET MAUI Android builds (particularly with newer Android SDK build tools) require JDK 17, but there can be compatibility issues. Let me think more carefully...\n\n\nThe real culprit is usually that .NET 8+ MAUI ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17 and uses that by default, so if JAVA_HOME is pointing elsewhere, it creates conflicts. The Temurin JDK 17.0.12 should work fine, but the issue is likely that the environment variable is either not set correctly or multiple JDK installations are interfering with each other. The real issue is that .NET MAUI doesn't actually use `JAVA_HOME` by default—it relies on the JDK bundled with the android workload instead. So even though they have Temurin set up correctly, the build is likely failing because either the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK isn't installed or the MSBuild property `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` isn't pointing to the right location. The fix would be to either reinstall the android workload or explicitly configure the project to use their Temurin installation. I'm realizing that .NET 8+ MAUI bundles its own JDK through the Android workload and doesn't rely on the system `JAVA_HOME`, so even with Temurin installed and properly configured, the build might still fail if the bundled JDK is missing or corrupted. The most likely fixes are reinstalling the workload or explicitly pointing the project to the Temurin installation path.","outputTokens":2559},"id":"35950547-ee9a-4a06-afad-007163c911ac","timestamp":"2026-04-09T15:19:12.272Z","parentId":"97c22da4-28ad-4fbc-adf7-068233c6e51e"}
